\
The nucleus of Helium contains two protons and two neutrons, which account for nearly all the mass of the atom. The two electrons of Helium are moving around the nucleus in very particular orbits. It turns out, due to the laws of quantum mechanics, that there are only a few specific orbits allowed around the atom. The orbits closer in are lower energy levels and orbits further out are higher energy levels. I have to note that I\'92ve drawn Helium using what\'92s called the Bohr model of the atom that looks like planets orbiting a star. In truth the electrons aren\'92t hard balls that zip around the nucleus but are more like a wavy-cloud that shifts its density around the nucleus. Yet the Bohr model is useful for illustrating how photons are absorbed and emitted by atoms:\
\
FIG: He atom absorbing and emitting photons, which are depicted by a wavy squiggled arrow. This illustration shows 5 energy levels though in actuality there are many more.\
\
We learned in the previous chapter that photons are packets of energy, the amount of which is determined by the frequency, \\(\\nu\\), of the photon \\(E=h\\nu\\). As we see in this above figure, if an electron absorbs a photon, the energy of the photon goes into jumping the electron into a higher energy level. A little strangely, the photon energy must be <em>precisely</em> the energy required for the jump. This implies that only photons of relatively few specific frequencies can be absorbed by a given atom; for this jump from energy level 1 to energy level 3 in the illustration, \\(E_3-E_1=h\\nu_\{1-3\}\\), where \\(\\nu_\{1-3\}\\) is the specific frequency of the photon for this situation. It\'92s a very similar process for photon <em>emission</em>: electrons move from a high energy level to a lower energy level by emitting a photon of precisely the right frequency to make up the difference in energy for the jump. Electrons prefer to be in the lowest energy level they can and will spontaneously emit photons to get there. But once an electron is in the lowest energy level surrounding the nucleus, an electron can\'92t emit photons anymore and it can only move up again by absorbing them. Notice also from the figure that electrons can jump up or down multiple energy levels as long as the right frequency of photon is involved (Note: Quantum mechanics does technically forbid very specific kinds of photon energy level jumps, but that\'92s not essential to know for our purposes here). This whole process explains why we only saw a few radiation peaks in the emission spectrum of galaxy NGC 6052 (below); the emission was coming from Hydrogen and Helium gases and they can only emit particular frequencies of photons.\
\
FIG: galaxy NGC 6052\
\
Besides absorption and emission of photons within individual atoms, it\'92s also possible for groups of atoms, called molecules, to collectively absorb and emit photons. The large majority of atmospheric gases are groups of either two or three atoms, called diatomic molecules and triatomic molecules; examples include \\(\\text\{O\}_2\\), diatomic, and \\(\\text\{CO\}_2\\), triatomic. Like in atoms, the electrons in molecules shift around in a wavy-cloud of negative charge. In order for this electron cloud to absorb and emit photons its center of charge needs change speed or change direction. A molecule\'92s electron cloud can do this if the molecule as a whole rotates or vibrates in particular ways. Let\'92s look at some examples for diatomic and triatomic molecules:\
\
FIG: Molecular rotation and vibration modes. Protons are depicted using the symbol +. Electrons are illustrated with a \'91cloud\'92 surrounding the protons and by the symbol -. Photons being absorbed are illustrated by squiggly wave packet arrows. Non-squiggly arrows indicate the molecule stretching, rotating, or bending. Note that the triatomic rotation modes illustrated here also include a vibrational bending. Modified from Pierrehumbert, Principles of Planetary Climate, 2010.\
\
The top row of both the diatomic and triatomic molecules is the lowest energy state of the molecules. This is similar to when electrons are in the lowest energy level in an atom. The rows below that show the molecules absorbing photons and subsequently vibrating and rotating. Molecules are also able to vibrate and rotate at the same time, illustrated with the bending vibration in the triatomic \'91rotation\'92 column of the figure. \
\
Just like for atoms, a molecule <em>absorbs</em> a photon to go from a low energy state to a higher energy state and <em>emits</em> a photon to go from a high energy state to a lower energy state. For example, a triatomic molecule will emit a photon when it goes from a stretched-out high energy state to its lowest energy state. And also just like for atomic emission and absorption, the photon energy needs to be just the right amount for the molecule to vibrate or rotate in one of the limited number of ways that it is able to. For example, \\(\\text\{CO\}_2\\) is a triatomic molecule and its bending mode, illustrated in the \'91rotation\'92 column in the figure, absorbs photons with a wavelength of \\(15 \\mu \\text\{m\}\\), corresponding to the missing emission chunk centered on \\(667 \\text\{cm\}^\{-1\}\\) in the spectra of Mars and Earth that we saw previously; this particular bending of \\(\\text\{CO\}_2\\) is therefore responsible for almost the entire greenhouse effect on Mars and a large portion of the greenhouse effect on Earth (approximately 20%).\
\
The bending vibration mode of \\(\\text\{CO\}_2\\) is so important because it just so happens to overlap with an important section the blackbody emission spectrum of Earth. \\(\\text\{CO\}_2\\) has many atomic and molecular absorption energies, but just one of them really matters for Earth\'92s greenhouse effect. Whether a gas is radiatively important or not is entirely determined by this overlap between a gas\'92 photon absorption energies and a planet\'92s emission spectra. In general, atomic absorption requires the highest energy photons, followed by molecular vibration, followed by molecular rotation, see side Table. Since Earth, as well as many other planets, emits primarily infrared radiation, it turns out that vibrational and rotational modes of atmospheric gases dominate the greenhouse effect, see side Table.\
